a, as well as a historical narratology that discusses concepts such as the narrator or the literary character in ancient literary theory and practice.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aAntike. 4aGender Studies. 4aReden in der 1. Person Singular. 4aliterarische persona.  aantiquity.  afirst-person speech.  agender studies.  aliterary persona.1 aBasso, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumann, Helge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessone, Federica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordes, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordes, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFabre-Serris, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuhrer, Therese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuhrer, Therese, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHafner, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallett, Judith P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarich-Schwarzbauer, Henriette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauser, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeith, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayr, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoro, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharrock, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSissa, Giulia, ec